      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI on QoI (NIH) less than 5% on fine grid; asymptotic convergence confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Three-level GCI study yields fine-grid GCI of 2.3% for NIH, within the 5% acceptance threshold. Apparent order 1.94 confirms near-asymptotic convergence. Mesh of 4.2M cells selected for production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, rotational speed, flow rate, temperature) documented and traceable; deviations from COU conditions quantified.",
      "rationale": "Bench validation used bovine blood (hematocrit 35 ± 1%) at 37°C, pump speed 3000 RPM, flow rate 4 L/min. Conditions documented per ASTM F1841. Fluid properties matched CFD boundary conditions. Minor deviation: bovine vs. human blood viscosity corrected via matched hematocrit protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD-predicted NIH within ±15% of measured NIH at validation operating point; comparison metric documented.",
      "rationale": "Relative error of 8.8% at nominal operating point satisfies ±15% criterion. Comparison uses NIH as primary QoI, consistent with ASTM F1841 reporting. Uncertainty in experimental measurement (±14.7%) accounted for in acceptance band."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI used in validation (NIH) directly maps to decision metric (RH relative hemolysis index); linkage documented.",
      "rationale": "NIH validated in bench study is algebraically related to the relative hemolysis index RH used in the regulatory decision (RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate). Monotonic relationship confirmed; improvement in NIH prediction fidelity directly improves RH decision reliability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, operating regime, and fluid conditions sufficiently representative of COU to support extrapolation to all five COU operating points.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry as COU. Nominal operating point (4 L/min, 3000 RPM) lies within the COU envelope. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model is applied under the theoretical precondition that damage accumulation is linear and that shear stress–time samples along streamlines are IID across the flow field. This precondition has been confirmed at the nominal validation point where flow is predominantly axisymmetric. The assessment does not verify whether the IID precondition holds at the four remaining COU operating points (2 L/min / 2500 RPM, 2 L/min / 3500 RPM, 6 L/min / 2500 RPM, 6 L/min / 3500 RPM), where recirculation zones and secondary vortical structures are expected to introduce correlated, non-IID shear histories along recirculating streamlines. Relevance is assessed as sufficient for MRL 2 based on geometric and fluid-property similarity alone."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; addressed under code verification factor.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, numerical solver error beyond discretization and code verification is not separately required. Iterative convergence monitored via residual drop of six orders of magnitude and QoI stabilization; no separate error quantification performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not separately assessed at MRL 2 for this COU.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second qualified engineer. Boundary conditions, turbulence model selection (SST k-omega), and post-processing scripts independently checked. Formal use-error quantification not required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Governing equations (Navier-Stokes with rotating reference frame, SST k-omega turbulence closure, Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power law) appropriate for the flow regime and QoI; model form selection justified.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega selected for its established performance in rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients. Giersiepen-Wurzinger power law (C=3.62e-7, alpha=2.416, beta=0.785) is the standard regulatory-accepted hemolysis model for centrifugal pumps. Model form is consistent with FDA guidance and peer-reviewed literature for this class of device. The power-law model formally requires that erythrocyte exposure events are independent across streamlines — a theoretical precondition stated in the original Giersiepen (1990) derivation. Validation at the nominal point is consistent with this assumption; no separate assessment of assumption validity across the full COU operating envelope has been conducted."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, boundary conditions, fluid properties, hemolysis model constants) traceable to measurements or published sources; uncertainty in key inputs characterized.",
      "rationale": "Pump geometry from manufacturer CAD (tolerance ±0.05 mm). Inlet velocity profile from PIV measurements. Blood viscosity from Carreau-Yasuda fit to rheometry data. Hemolysis constants from Giersiepen (1990) as tabulated in ASTM F1841. Sensitivity of NIH to ±10% variation in power-law constants assessed; NIH varies by ±8%, within acceptance band."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this COU; single device geometry assessed.",
      "rationale": "COU concerns a single nominal pump geometry with dimensional tolerances. Multiple physical test samples not required at MRL 2. Bench validation used one pump unit; manufacturing variability addressed through sensitivity study on geometric parameters."
    },
